.TH WTF 1 "2026-05-20" "wtftools 0.0.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
wtf, wtftools \- one command to see what is going on with your Linux server
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B wtf
[\fIglobal-options\fR]
[\fICOMMAND\fR]
[\fIcommand-options\fR]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B wtftools
is a diagnostic CLI for Linux SREs and indie operators. It rolls
the typical \(lqfirst 10 commands\(rq of an incident investigation into a
single program. With no arguments it runs a health audit and prints a
green/yellow/red checklist.
.PP
The tool degrades gracefully when
.BR systemctl ,
.BR journalctl ,
.BR apt ,
or
.B timedatectl
are missing \(em those checks are simply marked
.BR [SKIP] .
Use
.B wtf doctor
to see exactly which capabilities are available on this host.
.SH COMMANDS
.TP
.B wtf audit
Run the health audit (default when no command is given). Combines 29+
built-in checks plus any user plugins. Each check produces a colored
.BR [OK] / [WARN] / [FAIL] / [SKIP]
row.
.TP
.B wtf info
One-page snapshot of the host: OS, kernel, uptime, load, memory, swap,
per-mount disk usage, top processes by CPU/RAM, network interfaces and
listening ports.
.TP
.B wtf services \fINAME\fR
Drilldown for one systemd service: ActiveState, SubState, Result,
UnitFileState, NRestarts, MemoryCurrent, listening ports owned by the
main PID, and the last N journal lines.
.TP
.B wtf logs
Recent ERROR-level (and worse) journal entries grouped by service.
.TP
.B wtf crontab
Validate every crontab on the host: \fI/etc/crontab\fR,
\fI/etc/cron.d/*\fR, \fI/var/spool/cron/crontabs/*\fR. Replaces and
supersedes the standalone \fBcheckcrontab\fR tool.
.TP
.B wtf explain
Suggest concrete actions for the current WARN/FAIL findings.
With
.B --prompt
prints an LLM-ready prompt for piping to claude/ollama/etc.
.TP
.B wtf serve\fR (also: \fBwtfd\fR)
Run as a daemon: periodic audit, HTTP API on
.B 127.0.0.1:8765
by default. Endpoints:
.IR / ,
.IR /healthz ,
.IR /audit ,
.IR /audit.json ,
.IR /audit.prom ,
.IR /history ,
.IR /snapshot/N .
Flags:
.BI --listen " HOST:PORT" ,
.BI --interval " SECONDS" ,
.BR --save ,
.BI --auth-token-file " PATH" .
A bundled systemd unit lives at
.IR scripts/wtfd.service .
.TP
.B wtf doctor
Self-diagnostic: which CLI tools and \fI/proc\fR files
.B wtftools
can use on this host.
.TP
.B wtf plugins
List discovered check plugins and their search directories.
.TP
.B wtf config
Print effective configuration values and search paths. With
.B --example
prints a fully-commented template.
.SH GLOBAL OPTIONS
.TP
.B -V, --version
Print version and exit.
.TP
.B --no-color
Disable colored output.
.TP
.B -v, --verbose
Show extra detail (e.g. failed unit names, OOM events).
.TP
.B -q, --quiet
Reduce logging output to ERROR level.
.TP
.B --config \fIPATH\fR
Stack an additional INI config file on top of the default search paths.
.SH AUDIT OPTIONS
.TP
.B --format {text,json}
Output format. Default: text.
.TP
.B --strict
Exit non-zero when WARN results exist too. By default only FAIL triggers exit 2.
.TP
.B --exit-zero
Always exit with code 0 (useful in shell pipelines).
.TP
.B --check \fINAME\fR
Run only the named check (repeatable). See
.B wtf audit --list-checks
for the list of names.
.TP
.B --ignore \fINAME\fR
Skip a check (by short-name) or a single result-name (e.g.
.IR "\(lqdisk /mnt/Backup\(rq" ).
Repeatable. Merges with config\(cqs
.I [ignore]
section.
.TP
.B --only \fIfail|warn|problem|skip|ok|all\fR
Show only results with the given status.
.TP
.B --since \fIHOURS\fR
Look-back window for OOM/auth/kernel-error checks. Default: 24.
.TP
.B --watch \fISECONDS\fR
Re-run the audit every N seconds (Ctrl-C to exit).
.TP
.B --brief, -b
One-line summary suitable for MOTD / SSH banners.
.TP
.B --serial
Disable parallel execution (debug).
.TP
.B --check-timeout \fISECONDS\fR
Per-check timeout in seconds. Default: 10.
.TP
.B --alert \fICMD\fR
Shell command to invoke when FAIL results exist. Audit summary is piped
to stdin. Sets env vars
.BR WTF_FAIL_COUNT ,
.BR WTF_WARN_COUNT ,
.BR WTF_HOST .
.TP
.B --alert-on \fIfail|warn|any\fR
When to fire
.BR --alert .
Default: only on FAIL.
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
All checks passed (or no FAIL results found).
.TP
.B 1
Warnings present and
.B --strict
was passed; or crontab errors found.
.TP
.B 2
At least one check returned FAIL.
.TP
.B 130
Interrupted by Ctrl-C.
.SH FILES
.TP
.I /etc/wtftools/config.ini
Primary config file.
.TP
.I /etc/wtf/config.ini
Alternative config file.
.TP
.I ~/.config/wtftools/config.ini
Per-user config file.
.TP
.I /etc/wtf/checks.d/
.TQ
.I /etc/wtftools/checks.d/
.TQ
.I ~/.config/wtftools/checks.d/
Plugin search directories. Drop in any executable script with the exit
code convention 0=ok, 1=warn, 2=fail, 77=skip.
.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
Default audit:
.B wtf
.TP
Only failures:
.B wtf audit --only fail
.TP
MOTD one-liner:
.B wtf audit --brief
.TP
Drill into nginx:
.B wtf services nginx
.TP
Recent errors aggregated by service:
.B wtf logs --since '6 hours ago' -p err
.TP
Pipe diagnosis to an LLM:
.B wtf explain --prompt | ollama run llama3
.TP
Alert on FAIL via email:
.B wtf audit --alert 'mail -s "wtf on $WTF_HOST" sre@example.com'
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR systemctl (1),
.BR journalctl (1),
.BR cron (8),
.BR crontab (5)
